The sync handler (handleSync) identifies which pages to regenerate through several steps:

1. After pulling the latest commits, it calls getDiffSinceCommit() to get the set of files that changed since repo.last_commit_sha. If the current commit SHA matches the stored SHA, or if no files changed, the handler returns early with no AI calls.

2. For changed files, rescanChangedFiles() is called first: it deletes old document rows and embedding chunks for those paths, re-runs scanRepository() on the clone, inserts fresh content, and (if embeddings are enabled) refreshes embeddings for just the changed files and rebuilds the ANN index.

3. updateAffectedPages() then loads all wiki_pages for the current wiki version and filters to those whose file_paths JSON array overlaps with the changed file set:
   const changedSet = new Set(changedFiles);
   const allAffected = wikiPages.filter((wp) => {
     const pagePaths = JSON.parse(wp.file_paths) as string[];
     return pagePaths.some((p) => changedSet.has(p));
   });

Pages whose assigned files are entirely unrelated to the changed set are skipped — the sync is surgical. Only overlapping pages are regenerated via generatePageUpdate(), which uses the UPDATE_SCHEMA with a noChangesNeeded boolean so the model can signal when the diff doesn't actually affect a page's content.

When full file contents are injected via the file-based fallback path, formatFilesForContext applies a hard cap at 100,000 characters total. Files that do not fit within that budget are listed at the end under 'Files omitted due to context limit' — they are not silently dropped; they are explicitly noted. Each file that does fit is formatted as a fenced code block: '### {path}
```{language}
{full file content}
```'.

For embedding-based retrieval (both constrained and hybrid), the character budget is maxContextChars (default 16,000, configurable up to 200,000 via settings). After scoring and sorting chunks, the retrieval code fills up to this budget and truncates the last chunk that would overflow with a '... (chunk truncated)' suffix, so partial chunk content is included rather than the chunk being dropped entirely.
